    <div class="post-container" id="fpc-4492511">
                      
		<div class="post" id="post-4492511">
		<div class="long">
			<div class="head">
									<div class="options">
						<a href="javascript:;" onclick="togglePostFold(event,4492511)" class="btn btn-default btn-small btn-sm">Fold</a>
					</div>
								<div class="title" id="post-title-4492511">
																		
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/tsercele" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2891035); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=2891035&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610203364" alt="Tsercele" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=2891035)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/tsercele" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2891035); return false;" >Tsercele</a></span> <span class="odate time_1581096566 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">07 Feb 2020 17:29</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-4492511">
									

<p>Hi, Ruby! Thank you for reading - I'm glad it's the intruiging kind of confusing, rather than just obtuse. Let's see whether I can clear some of this up for you.</p>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">+&nbsp;show&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">–&nbsp;hide&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<p>For the record, I haven't been writing Wren Masterson as a multiple system. They use different aliases to blend in with social contexts inside and outside the Veil (tradecraft!), but they only have one personality. They were assigned the name &quot;Anna Bojarski&quot; at birth, adopted &quot;The Developer&quot; as part of AWCY, and eventually left both those names behind because they didn't work anymore. Adopting a new identity isn't uncommon for transgender people, but things are extra complicated for Masterson, on account of their experience with Unwinding. It's sort of a pataphysics version of the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ship_of_Theseus" target="_blank">Ship of Theseus</a> problem: if you replace every single part of &quot;Anna Bojarski&quot;, is &quot;Wren Masterson&quot; the same person afterwards? What if they don't want to be that person anymore? Can you leave the worst parts of yourself in the past, while still taking responsibility for the things you've done?</p>
<blockquote>
<p>individual possessing poorly understood anomalous abilities apparently relating to pataphysical manipulation and anomalous filmography</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Accurate! Penelope Gore's best guess is that Masterson is a reality bender, but she doesn't have the means to confirm it on her own (Scranton anchors aren't easy to come by), and she can't bring it up with the Foundation without getting both of them in deep, deep trouble.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>abilities appear to be part of, or interacting with, underlying dissociative disorders</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Also accurate! Masterson's abilities, worldview and psychological issues inform each other, but not in a particularly healthy way. In writing this story, I don't want to give the impression that mental illness is itself a superpower; if anything, I think living with derealization in a <a href="http://www.scp-wiki.net/sandrewswann-s-proposal">fictional universe</a> would make things even harder. Hence Wren's issues with &quot;tracking&quot;.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>may even differ in abilities or physical attributes</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Like I said, I'm not writing Wren with multiple personalities; they've got one core set of anomalous abilities, and their uncertainty when looking in a mirror is generally related to dissociation and dysphoria. Although&#8230; <span class="dblock">does a fictional character even have physical attributes, besides those described in the text?</span></p>
<blockquote>
<p>the Loop and the Jam</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Correct!</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Unwinding</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Close! Without spoiling too much, <span class="dblock">the narrative backscatter isn't solely because of Unwinding's activation in 2008. It's also symbolically tied into what happened on July 23, 2019&#8230; whatever that was.</span> More detailed answers are coming soon!</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Also, what is a pattern screamer and why is it tagged?</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Pattern screamers are one of my favorite parts of the SCP Wiki mythology, in part because they're so abstract and weird. Examples include <a href="/scp-3930">SCP-3930</a> (which does not exist) and <a href="/scp-4314">SCP-4314</a> (highly irrational math). My interpretation is that pattern screamers are a reflection of conscious observation: when you gaze into the abyss, you impose meaning on it, and the abyss is not thrilled. The pattern screamer in &quot;The Not-Too-Distant Future&quot; is <span class="dblock">growing in the collapsibles, the cracks in the narrative, using junk data to assemble itself into a coherent entity.</span> As for why it exists&#8230; <span class="dblock">what happens when someone realizes there's a murderer-shaped hole in the universe? What happens when the murderer-shaped hole &quot;remembers&quot; who they wanted to kill in the first place?</span></p>
<p>Here's the timeline from my end, minus the parts in Spoiler Country:</p>
<ul>
<li>1886: Samuel Tilford murdered by an unknown party. This becomes the only notable part of local history, yet Wren never hears about it.</li>
<li>2003: While living with her grandfather, Anna Bojarski discovers her anomalous influence over film and magnetic storage.</li>
<li>[SCENES MISSING] - <em>coming soon!</em></li>
<li>2008: Unwinding's debut exhibition kills six members of AWCY. After her inexplicable return, &quot;Anna&quot; is befriended by Felix Kipp, who helps her recover and find a new path.</li>
<li>[SCENES MISSING]</li>
<li>2015: JJ invites Wren Masterson into Gamers Against Weed.</li>
<li>2017: Wren concocts SCP-4581 (the Loop and the Jam) to deplatform their racist grandfather, Harold Bojarski. A month later, they send it to polaricecraps, who loses it at a rally. The tape ends up at Foundation Site-76, where Penelope Gore accidentally causes a containment breach.</li>
<li>2018: Gore interrogates Masterson at Site-201. Not long afterwards, she is recruited for Project CLOWNFISH, and (reluctantly) starts building a cover as &quot;whistl_stahp&quot;.</li>
<li>[SCENES MISSING] - <em>coming soon!</em></li>
<li>2019: Masterson rolls the dice and asks Gore for help containing Unwinding. When Penelope asks about local history, Wren has no knowledge of Tilford's Folly.</li>
<li>July 23, 2019: [DATA EXPUNGED]</li>
<li>July 24-27: Waking up post-amnesticization and discovering that Felix Kipp is dead, our protagonists do a little detective work and conclude that the events of the 23rd were pataphysically altered to be mundane. While Masterson is satisfied with this answer, Gore is worried by the possibility of loose ends, and keeps digging.</li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
</div>

